1. Architectural Goals
The TrashTalkSecurity architecture is designed to:

Support application security (AppSec) learning, not exploitation
Emphasize code analysis, SAST-style reasoning, and remediation
Remain simple to evolve as new labs and languages are added
Demonstrate production-quality engineering practices (CI/CD, Kubernetes)
Avoid premature complexity (e.g., microservices)

Architecture choices intentionally favor clarity, modularity, and correctness over scale-for-scale’s-sake.

2. Technology Choices
Primary Programming Language
Python
Chosen because:

Strong alignment with AppSec tooling and workflows
Excellent support for static analysis, AST parsing, and rule evaluation
Enables fast authoring of SAST-style labs and vulnerable examples
Widely used by real-world AppSec teams for automation and triage

Python is used for:

Backend API
Lab engine
Grading and validation logic
Vulnerable demo applications (where applicable)


Backend Framework
FastAPI
Chosen because:

Strong typing and clear contracts (OpenAPI)
Clean separation between API and business logic
Dependency injection suited for modular design
Async-first where needed, without forcing it everywhere


Data Store
PostgreSQL
Used for:

User accounts
Lab metadata
Completion and progress tracking

Relational storage is preferred for clarity and auditability.

Infrastructure

Docker – packaging
Kubernetes – deployment and runtime orchestration
CI/CD – automated build, test, and deploy
Infrastructure-as-Code – reproducible environments

Kubernetes exists to support the platform, not the learning content.

3. High-Level Architecture Pattern
✅ Modular Monolith (Authoritative Decision)
The system is intentionally built as a modular monolith.
This provides:

Clear logical boundaries
Single deployable artifact
Easy reasoning and testing
Low operational overhead
Future-friendly refactoring (modules can later become services if needed)

Microservices are explicitly out of scope for v1.

