5. Module Responsibilities
5.1 Authentication Module

User registration and login
Password handling and session management
Role enforcement (User / Admin)


5.2 Lab Engine Module
Core of the platform
Responsibilities:

Load lab definitions (labs-as-code)
Provide context and artifacts (code, apps)
Enforce lab constraints
Coordinate grading

Labs are treated as data + rules, not procedural code.

5.3 Grading & Evaluation Module
Responsible for:

Validating user answers
Rule-based reasoning checks
Pattern and logic evaluation
Returning structured feedback

Key constraint:

Labs are validated by reasoning and remediation correctness — never by exploit success.


5.4 Content Module

Stores and versions lab definitions
Maps labs to OWASP / CWE categories
Supports multiple languages per lab type over time

Labs are versioned alongside application code.

5.5 User & Progress Module

Tracks completed labs
Stores pass/fail state and results
Optional scoring (non-competitive)


6. Labs-as-Code Design
Labs are defined declaratively and stored in-repo.
Example structure:
labs/
  sast/
    sql_injection_basic/
      lab.yaml
      vulnerable.py
      secure.py
  api/
    broken_auth/
      lab.yaml
      app.py

Each lab MUST define:

Learning objective
Vulnerable implementation
Expected secure remediation
Validation rules
Guided explanations

This enables:

Peer review
CI validation
Easy contribution
Zero runtime coupling


7. Vulnerable Application Runtime (Controlled)
Some labs may include runnable applications.
Constraints:

Minimal Flask or FastAPI apps
Ephemeral lifecycle
No persistence
No external access
Optional to complete the lab

Understanding the code is more important than running the app.

8. Deployment Architecture
While learning is AppSec-focused, the platform itself demonstrates modern DevOps practices.

Single monorepo
CI pipeline:

Platform tests
Lab schema validation
Static checks


Kubernetes deployment:(this will be a v2 deployment, not a v1 focus at this moment in time, schedulued for later project date)

API deployment
Optional worker pods
Ephemeral lab containers


Automatic teardown of temporary resources


9. Security Architecture Principles

No real-world targets
No exploit payload execution required
Labs fully self-contained
Strict isolation between sessions
No long-lived secrets inside labs


The platform teaches defense — it must embody defense.


10. Non-Goals (Architectural)
This architecture explicitly avoids:

Microservice sprawl
Asynchronous messaging systems (for v1)
Distributed task queues
Event sourcing
Cloud misconfiguration labs

If a feature increases architectural complexity without improving AppSec learning, it is rejected.

11. Evolution Strategy
Planned future enhancements:

Additional programming languages for labs
More advanced SAST reasoning scenarios
Optional integration-style labs (CI feedback simulation)

Architectural invariants must remain intact:

AppSec-first
Code-centric
Reasoning-driven
Modular design


